{"warnings":{"query":{"*":"Formatting of continuation data will be changing soon. To continue using the current formatting, use the 'rawcontinue' parameter. To begin using the new format, pass an empty string for 'continue' in the initial query."}},"query":{"pages":{"8685753":{"pageid":8685753,"ns":0,"title":"Montana (comics)","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Notability|date=March 2014}}\n{{Merge to|Enforcers (comics)|date=March 2014}}\n{{Superherobox| <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image=[[File:Daredevil vol. 2, 102 (Jan, 2008) artwork.jpg|250px]]\n|caption=Cover art for ''Daredevil'' (vol. 2) #102.<br>Art by [[Marko Djurdjevic]].\n|comic_color=background:#ff8080\n|character_name=Montana\n|real_name=Jackson W. Brice\n|species=\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' #10 (Mar 1964)\n|creators=[[Stan Lee]] and [[Steve Ditko]]\n|alliance_color=background:#c0c0ff\n|alliances=[[Enforcers (comics)|Enforcers]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=\n|}}\n'''Montana''' ('''Jackson W. Brice''') is a fictional character in the [[Marvel Universe]].\n\n==Publication history==\nMontana first appeared in ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' #10 (March 1964), and was created by [[Stan Lee]] and [[Steve Ditko]].\n\nThe character subsequently appears in ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' #14 (July 1964), #19 (December 1964), ''The Amazing Spider-Man Annual'' #1 (1964), ''Marvel Team-Up'' #39-40 (November\u2013December 1975), ''The Spectacular Spider-Man'' #19-20 (June\u2013July 1978), ''Dazzler'' #7-8 (October\u2013September 1981), ''Marvel Team-Up'' #138 (February 1984), ''Tales of the Marvels: Inner Demons'' #1 (1996), ''Civil War: War Crimes'' #1 (February 2007), ''Daredevil'' #99-100 (September\u2013October 2007), #102 (January 2008), and ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' #562-563 (August 2008).\n\nMontana appeared as part of the \"Enforcers\" entry in the ''[[Official Handbook of the Marvel Universe|Official Handbook of the Marvel Universe Deluxe Edition]]'' #4.\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nJackson Brice was born in [[Bozeman, Montana]]. Along with [[Fancy Dan]] and the original [[Ox (comics)|Ox]], he was a founding member of the [[Enforcers (comics)|Enforcers]].{{Issue|date=January 2011}} He has great proficiency with the [[lasso|lariat]].\n\nMontana, Fancy Dan and Ox make their first appearance under the employ of the [[Frederick Foswell|Big Man]] (Frederick Foswell). During this time they have their first run-in with their longtime nemesis Spider-Man. During their first fight against the web-slinger, Montana's lasso skills initially prove successful but Spider-Man defeats the trio.{{Issue|date=May 2011}}\n\nOver the next couple of years, Montana and the team would be employed by [[Lightmaster]] in one of his many schemes, again bringing them into conflict with Spider-Man, with similar results.{{Issue|date=May 2011}} They would then lend their services to Tech-Master in his revenge plot against Harry S. Osgood, only to be defeated by Dazzler.{{Issue|date=May 2011}} Montana and the team would also go up against [[She-Hulk]] at one point.{{Issue|date=May 2011}}\n\n===Post-Civil War===\nMontana alongside Ox and Fancy Dan came back together to work for [[Mister Fear]], which pitted them directly against [[Daredevil (Marvel Comics)|Daredevil]].{{Issue|date=January 2011}} After Mister Fear's arrest, the Enforcers are taken in by the [[Hood (comics)|Hood]]'s organization.{{Issue|date=January 2011}}\n\n===Brand New Day===\nFollowing the events of ''[[Spider-Man: Brand New Day]]'', the Enforcers are patrons at the [[Bar With No Name]]. they take bets with a person calling himself \"The Bookie\", over whether Spider-Man will show up to battle \"Basher\", an unknown villain who claimed to have fought Spider-Man. Spider-Man shows up, but is revealed to be a fake when the real web-head shows up. The Enforcers decide to get revenge on The Bookie, capturing him. The Bookie's father calls Spider-Man for assistance, and he agrees to help. Spider-Man defeats Fancy Dan and Montana.{{Issue|date=January 2011}}\n\n===Big Time===\nIn the story arc, \"Kill To Be You\", Montana is the [[Kingpin (comics)|Kingpin]]'s right-hand man, and shows contempt toward the new [[Phil Urich|Hobgoblin]] (Phil Urich). When Spider-Man and [[Black Cat (comics)|Black Cat]] come to steal back the Reverbium, he falls out a window to his death while Hobgoblin saves Kingpin. Hobgoblin cruelly joked that \"he'll be missed by everyone - except the pavement\".<ref>''The Amazing Spider-Man'' #651</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\n===Earth X===\nIn the ''[[Earth X]]'' reality, Montana had mutated where he developed the ability to change his hands into lassos. He and his fellow Enforcers would be hired as heavies to protect President Norman Osborn. This protection proved to be ineffectual when the Skull came to New York to take over America. He took control of Montana and the others and then murdered Osborn. Montana's fate following the defeat of the Skull remain unrevealed.<ref>''Earth X'' #9</ref>\n\n===Marvel Noir===\nMontana and the other Enforcers are muscle for crime boss known as the Goblin (Norman Osborn).<ref>''Spider-Man Noir'' #1</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Montana===\nThe character's [[Ultimate Marvel]] incarnation's real name is '''Montana Bale'''. Along with the other Enforcers, he is an employee of the Kingpin of crime in New York.<ref>''Ultimate Spider Man'' #10</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n* Montana appeared in the 1967 ''[[Spider-Man (1967 TV series)|Spider-Man]]'' TV series. This version is referred to as '''Cowboy''' and was portrayed as being more intelligent. He works with [[Ox (comics)|Ox]] as they're hired to steal blueprints for the Plotter. \n\n[[Image:spectacularshocker.jpg|240px|right|thumb|Montana as Shocker in ''[[The Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)|The Spectacular Spider-Man]]''.]]\n* Montana appears in ''[[The Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)|The Spectacular Spider-Man]]'', voiced by [[Jeff Bennett]]. This version is the [[Enforcers (comics)|Enforcers]]' field leader, a trained mercenary, and the series incarnation of the \"'''[[Shocker (comics)|Shocker]]'''\".<ref name=Shocker>{{cite web|title=The Spectacular Spider-Man Past and Future part one|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/884/884897p1.html|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=27 June 2008}}</ref> He is a major antagonist in the [[Survival of the Fittest (The Spectacular Spider-Man)|pilot episode]] with his fellow Enforcers hired by the [[Tombstone (comics)|Big Man]] to eliminate [[Spider-Man]] but instead the Enforcers were defeated. While [[Fancy Dan]] and Ox are arrested, he's the only one that manages to escape. Montana returns as Shocker in the episode \"[[Market Forces (The Spectacular Spider-Man)|Market Forces]]\" after using stolen TRICORP gauntlets to continue his mission of finishing Spider-Man and is able to defeat Spider-Man with ease. But after realizing Spider-Man is still alive, Shocker fights Spider-Man again at a condemned theater and is defeated when the whole building is brought down on top of him. Montana is then shown webbed up with his Shocker costume on the ground as the police arrive.<ref>{{Cite episode |title = Market Forces |episodelink = Market Forces (The Spectacular Spider-Man)|url = |series = The Spectacular Spider-Man |serieslink = The Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)|credits = |network = |station = |city = |airdate = |began = |ended = |season = |seriesno = |number = |minutes = |transcript = |transcripturl = |quote = }}</ref> Montana/Shocker busts out of jail in the episode \"Group Therapy\" along with [[Vulture (comics)|Vulture]], [[Electro (Marvel Comics)|Electro]], [[Sandman (Marvel Comics)|Sandman]], [[Rhino (comics)|Rhino]] and [[Doctor Octopus]] to form [[Sinister Six|a group of supervillains]] to defeat Spider-Man. After he takes part in the group's victory over Spider-Man during their first fight, the group's rematch has Spider-Man (under the [[Symbiote (comics)|Symbiote]]'s influence) defeating Shocker once again after his gauntlets are removed/destroyed then he's knocked unconscious.<ref>{{Cite episode |title = Group Therapy |episodelink = |url = |series = The Spectacular Spider-Man |serieslink = The Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)|credits = |network = |station = |city = |airdate = |began = |ended = |season = |seriesno = |number = |minutes = |transcript = |transcripturl = |quote = }}</ref> Montana returns in the episode \"Probable Cause\". With his Shocker gauntlets modified by the [[Tinkerer]], Montana works with Ricochet and Ox as the [[New Enforcers]] but they're eventually stopped by Spider-Man after [[Hammerhead (comics)|Hammerhead]] double-crossed them.<ref>{{Cite episode |title = Probable Cause |episodelink = |url = |series = The Spectacular Spider-Man |serieslink = The Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)|credits = |network = |station = |city = |airdate = |began = |ended = |season = |seriesno = |number = |minutes = |transcript = |transcripturl = |quote = }}</ref> In the episode \"Opening Night\", Montana and the other Enforcers are seen as inmates at the [[Vault (comics)|Vault]]. When released by the [[Norman Osborn|Green Goblin]], Montana and the other inmates try to capture Spider-Man but they're all recaptured by [[Walter Hardy|another inmate]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title = Opening Night |episodelink = |url = |series = The Spectacular Spider-Man |serieslink = The Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)|credits = |network = |station = |city = |airdate = |began = |ended = |season = |seriesno = |number = |minutes = |transcript = |transcripturl = |quote = }}</ref> Series producer [[Greg Weisman]] made a creative choice to make Montana, instead of [[Shocker (comics)|Herman Schultz]], into Shocker during production of this series into Shocker.<ref>http://s8.org/gargoyles/askgreg/latest.php</ref>\n\n* Montana appears in the ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)|Ultimate Spider-Man]]'' cartoon series episode \"Nightmare on Christmas\", voiced by [[Troy Baker]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.comicvine.com/montana/29-6767/ Montana] at Comicvine\n\n{{Daredevil}}\n{{Spider-Man}}\n{{Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)}}\n\n[[Category:Characters created by Stan Lee]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Steve Ditko]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1964]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Montana]]\n[[Category:Fictional cowboys and cowgirls]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics supervillains]]\n[[Category:Spider-Man characters]]"}]}}}}